# Light & Dark Mode

All new UI must work in light and dark mode. This project uses **Tailwind v4** with CSS variables in `src/app/globals.css` and `prefers-color-scheme: dark` — not a `class="dark"` toggle.

## Use semantic tokens

Prefer theme tokens defined in `globals.css` / `@theme inline`:

| Token | Example classes |
|-------|-----------------|
| Surfaces | `bg-background`, `bg-surface` |
| Text | `text-foreground`, `text-muted`, `text-primary`, `text-accent` |
| Borders | `border-border` |
| Actions | `bg-primary`, `hover:bg-primary-light`, `bg-accent` |

```js
// ❌ BAD — hardcoded light-only colors
<p className="text-black bg-white">...</p>

// ✅ GOOD — tokens adapt via CSS variables
<p className="text-foreground bg-surface">...</p>
```

## Adding new colors

1. Add light value under `:root` and dark value under `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` in `globals.css`
2. Expose via `@theme inline` (e.g. `--color-brand: var(--brand)`)
3. Use the Tailwind utility (`text-brand`, `bg-brand`) in components

Do not ship new UI with colors that only look correct in one mode. If `dark:` variants are needed, pair them with a light default (see existing `page.js` patterns).

## Checklist for every new component

- [ ] Backgrounds and text use semantic tokens or paired `dark:` classes
- [ ] Borders, hovers, and focus rings are visible in both modes
- [ ] Images/icons account for dark backgrounds when needed (e.g. `dark:invert`)
